snippet.textDisplay: I too wanted rhinoplasty when I was a teenager for my big, bumpy nose and my tiny boobs. Now, after working on my self confidence, I can't even imagine spending such crazy amount of money just so other people could find me a bit more beautiful. Look at it like this: what kind of person would you rather talk to? One that has a pretty nose, or one that has an imperfect nose, but spent the money on a trip and has interesting stories from that trip? You can have plastic surgery, but the self confidence issues will still be there. One thing I learned was that all our physical flaws look much worse in our eyes then they really are.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's sort of a question of what ends you find preferable to decide whether or not you should be judgmental towards people who get plastic surgery... Do you find it preferable that people get a lot of plastic surgery to try to look like some perfect Barbie doll or something because they aren't satisfied (and may never be) with who they are? Or do you find it preferable that people who just want a little plastic surgery should not be judged?

Obviously this is kind of a false dichotomy and the ideal thing would be a happy medium, but it's also difficult to know where that happy medium is... Like, you probably want to allow for trans people to do enough surgery to try and get a grasp on their identity and what not, but you also don't really want those people who feel miserable unless they can look like Brittany Spears does on the Photoshopped magazine covers... And then when they don't they just end up feeling both miserable and impoverished...

I think the people who judge those who got plastic surgery though are still doing it due to good intentions, like they want these people to be happy with who they are... But at the same time sometimes surgery can really help with that... But at the same time, sometimes surgery seems like it could help, but it actually can't...
